2. Page Fault Exceptions (Required by Linux)
Why you need it: Linux does not load programs into physical RAM immediately. It creates "Empty" page tables (Valid = 0). When a program tries to run, it hits an empty page, the CPU triggers a Page Fault, and Linux pauses the program to load the data from the SD Card into RAM.
Right now, your software walker's FAULT: label just prints ! and mrets. Linux will be stuck in an infinite loop.
The Fix: Your software walker must be able to tell the Hardware to trigger a Page Fault.
Create a new Magic Address in Verilog (e.g., 0xF0004).
Have the Software Walker write the bad Virtual Address to 0xF0004.
The Verilog catches this write and triggers Exception 12 (Instruction Page Fault), 13 (Load Page Fault), or 15 (Store Page Fault) based on what mmu_pc or mmu_da was doing.
3. Page Permissions R/W/X/U (Required by Linux)
Why you need it: Linux protects kernel memory from user programs. A user program (U-mode) is not allowed to read a page unless the U bit (bit 4) is 1 in the PTE. A program is not allowed to write to a page unless the W bit is 1.
Right now, your Hardware TLB only stores the PPN (tlb_ppn). It does not store permissions, so it allows anything to read/write to any mapped page!
The Fix:
In your mmu assembly, when you write to the TLB magic address, write the ENTIRE 64-bit PTE (x4), not just the PPN (x7).
In your Verilog Hardware TLB, add a new array: reg [7:0] tlb_flags [0:3];
When the Hardware TLB matches a virtual address, check the flags!
If it is an Instruction Fetch, but X is 0 -> Trigger Instruction Page Fault.
If it is a Store, but W is 0 -> Trigger Store Page Fault.
If current_privilege_mode == U_mode but U is 0 -> Trigger Page Fault.
4. Standardize the CLINT (Timer) and PLIC
Why you need it: OpenSBI has platform code built-in. If you use the standard "QEMU Virt" or "SiFive" memory addresses, OpenSBI will work out-of-the-box without you having to write custom C code for OpenSBI.
CLINT Base: 0x0200_0000
MSIP: 0x0200_0000 (Write 1 to trigger Software Interrupt)
MTIMECMP: 0x0200_4000
MTIME: 0x0200_BFF8
UART Base: Usually 0x1000_0000 (16550A UART standard).
You already have mtime and mtimecmp connected perfectly to the bus! You just need to make sure your address decoding (Mtime_selected, Mtimecmp_selected, etc.) matches the official RISC-V physical addresses so OpenSBI knows where to find them.
